CLINICAL HISTORY:  Epilepsy, currently seizure-free.
MEDICATIONS:   Lamictal, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A 38-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy, current seizure­
free.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Digital video EEG is performed using standard
10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation. This is an awake through stage II sleep record in an individual who is very drowsy.
In maximum wakefulness there is an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm. Vertex waves are noted in sleep, as are post.
Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background slowing. The patient is falling asleep in photic stimulation.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits but excessively drowsy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features are noted. The excessive drowsiness can be due to sleep deprivations, medications or a warm environment.

CLINICAL HISTORY:    38 year old right handed woman with migraine headaches, depression and a sharp pain in her head.
MEDICATIONS: Xanax, Seroquel, Zolpidem, Nabumetone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness background EEG is well-organized. There is a relatively fast alpha rhythm of 12 Hz with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation produces an increased in amplitude of the background. This is followed by a drowsy and then stage I sleep with vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation are performed concurrently and do not active the record. In fact, the patient seems to drift into stage II sleep at the close of this study.
HR: 	66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal
EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 81 year old right handed woman evaluated for seizure versus syncope. History of hypertension.
MEDICATIONS: Simvastatin, Calcium, Lisinopril, Vit, B12
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is
appropriately organized for age with a 10 Hz 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the record. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are identified. The bad electrode should have been fixed during the study.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   37 year old woman requires neurologic clearance for foot surgery. Seizure free for the last 2 years.

MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, background EEG includes a well organized 9.5 hertz 40 microvolts posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.

HR:   78 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no focal nor epileptiform features noted in this record. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing sleep may be of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old right handed woman with episodes of loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: Prochlorperazine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Brief drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta. Hyperventilation produces and increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 56 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are identified.
Evaluation for the bradycardia may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed male with seizure versus syncope versus hypoglycemic attack.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, symmetric reactive alpha rhythm. The patient quickly becomes drowsy and when he does so rhythmic slowing of the alpha rhythm is noted. Hyperventilation also produces a small amount of background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits driving, but then the patient drifts off into sleep with theta in the background.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified. The previous EEG was not noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with learning disability, seizure free since
2007. Previous history of vertex sharp wave.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awaken and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively
low voltage. There is excess theta in the background and a hint of 9 Hz alpha rhythm.
Later portions of the record demonstrate a more vigorous 10 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response, but the patient is drifting into stage
2 sleep.
HR: 56 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed in this record
today. There were only on 1 occasion some focal theta in the right central temporal
region. The only other abnormality is really an excess of theta or a variable degree of
background slowing or disorganization. On the whole, these findings are less prominent
than in previous studies. Many years ago there was a vertex spike while awake, but that
was not seen today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old right handed male with post traumatic epilepsy, last seizure 2 weeks ago with·incontinence and tongue-biting during sleep. Co-morbid depression.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Valium, Prozac.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10.5 Hz, 60 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low. voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of frontal slowing. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to a previous study of September 6, 2007. Additional EEG recording or the use of special electrodes may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 33 year old male with new onset seizures. Tonic-clonic activity versus panic attack in a motor vehicle accident.

MEDICATIONS: None.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of. EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and a small increase in theta. Photic stimulation does not activate the record. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old right handed woman, 13-weeks pregnant, with recurrent syncopal events.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG performed in lab was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not done.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a well developed, appropriately high amplitude posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. There is occasional electrode artifact, but the tech notes that the patient just had a hair weave removed and the scalp is quite oily. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no focal nor epileptiform features observed. However, if epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study capturing sleep may be needed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 26 year old right handed male with migraine headaches, bipolar disease, anxiety, multiple concussions and epilepsy, with last seizure January 4, 2010. History of loss of consciousness and confusion with this seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Seroquel, Depakote, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. There is a fair amount of muscle artifact observed in the background.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 65 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm, and a small amount of low voltage frontal central beta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. This is followed by drowsiness with anterior spread with alpha rhythm. POSTS are observed in stage 1 sleep. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief sleep.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were noted, but if epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 51-year-old woman with a lifelong history of tonoclonic seizures but with an atypical spell characterized by confusion and incontinence, also with dyskinesias of the jaw.
MEDICATIONS: Nitroglycerin, Flovent, ASA, Protonix, Dilantin, Dilaudid, Lovenox, Metoprolol, Lisinopril
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. This is an awake through stage II sleep record with photic simulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is within normal limits with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm. In the transition to sleep, there are vertex waves, K complexes, spindles; and on 1 or 2 occasions, some frontal vertex waves which is a little higher amplitude on the left or right. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is falling into stage II sleep and produces scant driving.
HR: 70 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: If further characterization of this patient's epilepsy is important, a more prolonged sleep recording, particularly looking for a frontal lobe focus, may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 54-year-old woman with mood swings, personality changes, pituitary surgery, and blindness.
MEDICATIONS: Hydrocortisone, lisinopril, aspirin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a well-defined 10.3 Hz central MU rhythm. An alpha rhythm is also discernible at 8.5 Hz. The overall pattern is relatively low voltage. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Heart rate 72 b.p.m.
IMPRESSION: Low voltage but otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The MU rhythm described above is a normal finding.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 11 year old right handed female with episodes of staring and difficulty responding for which the patient was amnestic. Past history of fainting and a family history of epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is 11 Hz alpha rhythm. The overall record is appropriately organized for age. Features of drowsiness include increased background slowing with vertex waves in sleep. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude in the background. Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were observed and the normal developmental milestones for a child of this age including hypnagogic hypersynchrony were observed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 17 year old right handed female with recurrent tonic-clonic seizures characterized by blurry vision, generalized shaking, and unresponsiveness. Currently 12 weeks pregnant.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Patient is quite drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5-Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Central mu rhythm is observed as is generous frontocentral beta. Vertex waves and spindles are observed in stage 1 sleep. Normal juvenile patterns of arousal with some hypersynchronous slowing are observed. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting in and out of sleep, but there is a generous photic driving response noted during photic stimulation.
HR: 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Normal record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 19-year-old woman, 26 weeks pregnant, with staring spells, episodes of poor responsiveness with shaking.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record in a very sleepy individual.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of this EEG includes abundant stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS. In maximal wakefulness the background EEG includes a 9.5-Hz alpha rhythm with head rocking artifact. The patient quickly drifts back to stage 2 sleep.
Heart rate 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The hypersomnolence is the most remarkable feature about this record. These findings can be seen in the context of sleep deprivation or the use of medications. Additional evaluation for other causes of hypersomnolence may be considered. This record is a wonderful example of all the typical waveforms of stage 2 sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old woman with blackout spells occurring 2 to 3 times a
week. They are associated with head numbness, a funny, cold feeling running down
her back. Past history of childhood epilepsy and depression.

MEDICATIONS: Seroquel, Alprazolam

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm in a
background of generous beta and a scant amount of theta. Hyperventilation does not
activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Generous beta is a nonspecific finding but can be seen in
the context of anxiety or benzodiazepines. If this patient's spells are frequent, either a
repeat EEG capturing one of her events or an additional long-term EEG monitoring session may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 55-year-old gentleman with a history of dementia, depression and stroke who has had episodes of loss of awareness lasting 1-2 minutes occurring every 6-8 weeks.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid, Zoloft, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic simulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 10.3 Hertz alpha rhythm of 40 microvolts. Prominent eye movement artifact is observed.
Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. If epilepsy is an important consideration a repeat study either captured sleep or one of his specific events may be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 65 year old right handed female with an episode in November 2009 when the patient went to sleep and was unable to be awakened for a month. The patient was told that she had a seizure at that time.

MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab u·sing standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is remarkable for a generous quantity of background of beta. There is a well-defined alpha rhythm of 8. 7 Hz. Head rocking artifact is noted In the background. Hyperventilation produces hypersynchronous theta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG was within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is no epileptiform activity. There is a fair amount of head rocking artifact in the right posterior quadrant, but this does not otherwise preclude the interpretation of this record. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a more prolonged sleep study may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old male with dull frontal headache, difficulty with
concentrating and syncopal spells associated with visual scintillations. Attention deficit
disorder.

MEDICATIONS: Adderall

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. The technologist notes that the patient has an unusual hair
cut that makes it difficult for electrode placement.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with symmetric reactive 10.7 Hz alpha rhythm, a small amount of
frontocentral beta and central mu activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in
amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
Drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.

HR: 78 bpm.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this
record. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with epilepsy, seizure-free for some years.

MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.7 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.There is eye flutter artifact noted in wakefulness. In the transition to drowsiness, there is prominent theta activity. Vertex waves and spindles were observed in stage II sleep. Hyperventilation produces rhythmic frontal slowing. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed today. Of note, some prior EEGs have demonstrated a bit of background theta, a bit of disorganization or a vertex wave in wakefulness, however, these were not identified in this record.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old female with gastroparesis, currently unable to tolerate oral medications due to vomiting with 5-12 complex partial seizures today.

MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Benzodiazepines
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is described as somewhat disinhibited.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta. The patient is described as occasionally tense and as she tenses up, there is an increase in muscle artifact. Features of stage I sleep include vertex waves and spindles. The patient seems to stiffen up or to become tense and then drops into stage II sleep.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this EEG. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old male with a syncopal episode March 2, 2010.
MEDICATIONS: ASA, Zocor
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric, 10.5 alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with attenuation of alpha rhythm and the appearance of POSTS as well as vertex waves. Sleep is not sustained. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic stimulation elicits driving response.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptic form features are observed in this record. Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration a repeat tracing can be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old right handed male with epilepsy since age 5, last
seizure at age 16.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized
with 10.3 Hz alpha rhythm had a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral
beta activity. Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm with
rhythmic theta. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude. Photic stimulation
elicits scant driving. Occasional head rocking artifact is noted.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There were no epileptiform features noted. If epilepsy is
an important consideration, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep may be
considered. Alternatively, comparison with his childhood EEGs may also be of use.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 25 year old right handed woman with episodes of deja vu which
can be triggered by smells. Symptoms began in 2002. History of depression.
MEDICATIONS: Effexor, propranolol, Ortho Tri-Cyclen.
Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is
appropriately organized for a young adult with a 9.5 Hz, 50 to 60 microvolt posterior
dominant rhythm and posterior slow waves of youth. Electrode artifact is identified at T4.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. Photic
stimulation elicits bilateral driving. Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic theta.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
There was a single burst of right temporal slowing identified in drowsiness and this must
be considered artifactual as it occurred on only 1 occasion. To more completely
evaluate this young adult for complex partial epilepsy, a repeat tracing capturing sleep
or an outpatient ambulatory study capturing one of her spells Is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old right handed male with depression, cerebral palsy status post aneurysmal clipping and a tonic clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Zoloft, Dilantin, Norvasc
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. There is no mention of a craniotomy deformity. This is an awake record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 Hertz alpha rhythm with generous low voltage frontal central beta. Significant electrode artifact is noted in the right temporal region. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta with vertex waves. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. Consideration for an abnormality in the skull given the findings described above is suggested although none was reported by the tech. If epilepsy is an important consideration a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20

HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal

CLINICAL HISTORY: 21 year old right handed male with depression and insomnia.
Evaluate for temporal lobe epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: Unknown
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organizes It is relatively low voltage, but there is a well defined 11 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage frontal and central beta activity Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record. It produces an increase in heart rate from 72 bpm to
115 bpm. Features of drowsiness include rhythmic theta. Photic stimulation elicits
vigorous driving at 5 Hz.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does

CLINICAL HISTORY: 42 year old left handed woman with asthma, reflux, anxiety,
depression and epilepsy, evaluated for seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Synthroid, Dilantin, ASA, Ranitidine, Benadryl, Proventil, Zolpidem,
Diovan, Percocet
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 hertz alpha rhythm,
drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm followed by the appearance
of beta, Hyperventilation produces rhythmic background slowing. Photic stimulation is
performed while the patient is drifting off to sleep and elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features are observed. If this

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old right handed female with headaches, left temporal lobe epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Keppra

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm with 9 Hz central MU rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing some 5 Hz, rhythmic followed by bursts of rhythmic, Features of drowsiness include head rocking, artifact and an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no focal nor epileptiform features observed in this record. Multiple normal variants were noted. A normal EEG does not exclude diagnosis of epilepsy. Additional EEG recording may be helpful to characterize this individuals epileptiform activity as this is the second EEG without sharp waves or spikes.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 75 year old right handed woman with chronic subcortical infarcts, tremor, lupus, and heart failure.

MEDICATIONS: Metoprolol, Celexa, Ecotrin, Plavix, Synthroid, Isosorbide, Zocor, Micardis, Citalopram, Detrol, Protonix, Lovenox
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient seems to be drowsy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low-voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in the beta. Photic stimulation is remarkable for photoelectric artifact tremor and scant driving.

HR: 72 to 84 bpm with notched QRS.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. This is a normal EEG for an adult of this age.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 40 year old right handed male with chronic epilepsy, multiple suicide attempts, last seizure 1 month ago.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a low voltage, relatively tense appearing EEG with significant temporalis muscle artifact. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small increase in amplitude of the background. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved. Photic stimulation elicits driving response.
HR: 60 to 70 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. If epilepsy is an important consideration, please consider repeat study in the lab capturing deeper stages of sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 24-year-old female with cardiac pathology and life-time rare
episodes of loss of awareness without clear loss of consciousness. No tonic clonic
activity.

MEDICATIONS: Alprazolam, Metoprolol.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG monitoring. Hyperventilation and
photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a youthful, well-organized 11.7 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage with central beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of rhythmic theta. There is some slightly asymmetric eye movement artifact compatible with slight asymmetry in electrode placement. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features. If epilepsy is an important consideration, additional testing may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 35 year old right handed male with a 3 year history of epilepsy.
Seizures are characterized by light headedness, blurry vision with loss of consciousness
and are associated with alcohol withdrawal.

MEDICATIONS: Phenytoin, Tramadol, Ibuprofen, Cyclobenzaprine.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is well organized with a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation elicits driving. After photic stimulation is over, the patient had some jerking of her shoulders but not in association with the flashing lights. After the photic stimulation continues, the recording continues and the patient had intermittent jerking of her shoulders. The shoulders jerk forwards and backwards.

The shoulder jerking is not associated with epileptiform activity in the EEG. It is sometimes associated with upwards thrusting of her upper chest. She stares straight ahead during the events.

As the record continues, a physician examines the patient. The interaction with the physician and the patient is associated with increasing motor activity including eye blinking, mouth opening and closing, a little bit of alternating movements to right or left, and then some rotatory movements of the torso. When the movements stop, the EEG shows a normal awake pattern. The patient is staring off to space after the event ends.

The event begins at 9:58 and lasts 7 minutes. Afterwards, there is intermittent jerking. Cognitive testing is not performed to make certain that the patient is responsive at the end of the EEG.

HR: 60 bpm


IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a 7-minute behavioral episode without EEG change. This recording suggests a behavioral event rather than an electrical seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed gentleman with a long history of depression, epilepsy, cerebral palsy, subsequent aneurysm repair. Last seizure 05/11/2011 with loss of consciousness and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Dilantin, Norvasc, Simvastatin, Sertraline, Amlodipine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall EEG is relatively low voltage with generous beta and scant alpha rhythms. A breech rhythm is noted in the right hemisphere. There is also some electrode artifact, compatible with a deformity of the skull shape.
Hyperventilation is performed early in the record, producing an increase in the amplitude, augmenting the double phase reversing artifacts on the right and increasing some theta a bit more so on the right compared to the left. Features of drowsiness included increase in beta. In drowsiness, the focal slowing is a bit more apparent on the right with a mixture of rhythmic 3-5 Hz activity. Vertex waves are noted as the patient transitions in and out of sleep. There is  disruption of faster frequency activity on the right in the transition to sleep in the centrotemporal regions with a bit more prominent spindles in the central regions, in the region of the previous
craniotomy. Overall, most of the focal slowing in this record is centrotemporal. In the context of a breech rhythm, there are a handful of right central or frontal sharp waves. Photic stimulation is  performed while the patient is in stage 2 sleep. No significant driving response was noted.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: A normal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic theta and delta activity in the right temporal region.
2. Rare G4 and F4 sharp waves identified in the context of a breech rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, the EEG today has primarily centrotemporal slowing. The sharp waves are ipsilateral to the previous craniotomy and similar to the previous records. There is some variability in terms of localization of epileptiform activity
in the right for this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed woman with new onset of seizures who was unconsciousness, unable to speak, and left face twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Continuous spike detection software, as well as seizure detection software, patient events, and alarms, as well as nurses events were noted to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  In the middle of the night some electrodes became dislodged and there is some electrode artifact by the end of the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Activating procedures and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep and normal stages I to III with sleep are recorded.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
Episodes:  The patient had 3 episodes throughout the recording.  The first one occurred at 12:34 p.m. at the onset of the recording where she started having left facial twitching, followed by unresponsiveness while continuing to have left facial twitching.  This event lasted for about 2 minutes and then the patient became reactive again.
The second event occurred at 8:18 p.m.  The patient suddenly started having left facial twitching and grimacing, as well as tightening her arms, as well as becoming unresponsive.  This was followed by staring and mouth movements.  The episode lasted for over 4 minutes.
At about 3:32 a.m. the patient suddenly started having diffuse body shaking and rocking, as well as facial twitching.  This was much more severe than the other ones.  She continued rocking, jerking, and being unresponsive.  Then after stopping the jerking she laid in bed and remained unresponsive and started moving her mouth rhythmically in a chewing fashion.  The whole event lasted for about 4.5 minutes.
The EEG during the whole 3 events revealed a normal posterior dominant rhythm and no epileptiform correlate to any of the events.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG and 3 non-epileptic events.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  Note:  The 3 events described above did not have an EEG correlate which is consistent with a diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic seizures.

those with atherosclerotic disease risk factors.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study with more prolonged sleep can be obtained.

INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient recalls 3 episodes. Event time 9:58 p.m.  No abnormalities on the EEG were identified at that time.
Event time10:25 a.m.:  There was another burst lasting 4 seconds in duration in the morning on the 20th which is similar to the 2 prior bursts.   No clinical features were recalled.
HR:    60 bpm
INTERVAL IMPRESSION:  There are 3 bursts of rhythmic theta from the left temporal region with frequency evolution.  These are concerning as a potential interictal epileptiform discharge.  They may also be clinically significant with the mini-auras that the patient experienced.

Event time 11:55:  The patient pushes the button at 11:56:12 stating that she feels as if she is about to have an aura.  She puts her hand to her chest and later appears to be tearful.  The EEG is awake at this time.  No epileptiform features were noted.   For her 8:00 p.m. the patient reported symptoms that her throat was closing with the seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 49-year-old male with a history of seizures and hypertension presents with seizure-like activities described as acting weird, staring, confusion, and EMS noted generalized tonic-clonic seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include phenobarbital and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10/20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1-channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through a stage II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency and 30-35 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is presence of low amplitude diffuse beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage I sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background activity and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of the vertex sharp waves.  Stage II sleep was captured characterized by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles. Heart rate was 90-100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic metabolic hypoxic or infectious encephalopathy, alternatively it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including phenobarbital or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform discharges abnormalities or seizures were captured during this record.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.  The absence of epileptiform activities or seizures does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old man with history of seizures has been seizure-free for more than a year with mild mental retardation and developmental delay.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage 1 sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9-10 Hz seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  A stage 1 sleep is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well as the presence of vertex sharp waves and posts.  Hyperventilation results in symmetrical slowing of the background activity.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through stage 1 sleep.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG, does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 30 -year-old male with onset of seizures in March, 2012.  Most recent seizure was in February 2013.  Has an aura of sweating, migraine with loss of consciousness.

The patient is very sleepy and drifts in and out of sleep.  He quickly transitions into stage 2 sleep with appearance of spindles and K complexes.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed which showed a photic myogenic response and also bilateral driving response at intermediate/ frequencies.
Heart rate 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in a very sleepy patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or generalized epileptiform features were seen.  Normal EEG does not rule out epilepsy.  Clinical correlation indicated.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 25-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy.  First ever seizure 04/27 with loss of consciousness, twisting and post ictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Klonopin, previously treated with tramadol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
TECHNICAL:  The patient appears to be somewhat tense.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm.  During much of the EEG, there is a little bit more relaxed wakefulness with slowing of the alpha rhythm to 8.5 Hz.  Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in beta.  Other features of drowsiness include rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness with vertex waves noted in stage I sleep.
During hyperventilation and in relaxed wakefulness, there are 2 simple sharp waves.  During hyperventilation the simple sharp waves are more clearly defined after going slow wave.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for prominent beta and prominent, supraharmonic driving.
Additionally, hyperventilation was remarkable for a fair amount of muscle artifact.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrated multiple, normal variants, some of which have the morphology of benign epileptiform discharges.  There is a single left mid to posterior temporal sharp wave.  In that there is only one discharge, this must be considered artifactual.  The generous beta described above may be due to this patient's medications.
If an underlying seizure disorder is an important consideration, a followup study with more prolonged sleep is suggested.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 42-year-old woman with a history of seizures.  Her last seizure occurred about 1 week ago while the patient was asleep.  The seizure was described as generalized tonic/clonic convulsion.  Of note, the patient was just diagnosed with colon cancer.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude of 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates.  Bursts of diffuse high amplitude centrally predominant theta are captured.  Also symmetrical vertex sleep spindles and K complexes are observed.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetric driving at multiple flash frequencies. Excess diffuse beta is captured.
FINDINGS:
Stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 22-minute EEG.  Excess beta could be secondary to medication affect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old woman with epilepsy since the age of 8.  Most recent seizure June/July 2012 with fainting, falling, and shaking.  Now 4 months pregnant.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was an awake and asleep record.
TECHNICAL:  Impedances for most of the electrodes were satisfactory, but this EEG was problematic with a great degree of muscle artifact when the patient was awake.  As the patient went off to sleep, there was still muscle artifact picked up in the left scalp electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Despite the problems described above, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of focal frontal central beta.  Wicket was noted as the patient became drowsy.  Other features with drowsiness include rhythmic central theta.  The electrode artifact did not drop out in stage I sleep with vertex waves.  Brief stage II sleep included vertex waves with spindles.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was remarkable for a great deal of muscle artifact.  Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but otherwise normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The wicket is a normal finding.  Given the degree of muscle artifact described above, a follow-up study capturing perhaps more prolonged
sleep or with other mechanisms to alleviate the muscle artifact is suggested.  Alternatively, comparison with this individual's childhood EEGs may be of value.
